{"kind":"cannot-formalise","why":"Egalitarianism is a normative political doctrine and school of thought — a set of beliefs about how people *should* be treated and what *ought* to be valued. Its identity rests on abstract principles (social equality, moral status, rights, justice) and on contestable commitments about human nature and political organization. These are not grounded in perception, bodily action, concrete kinds, or the everyday sensory world. The prime lexicon contains no apparatus for formalizing ideological commitments, political ought-statements, or the complex normative reasoning required to distinguish egalitarianism from other political philosophies. This concept belongs to the social-philosophy sector, not the tier of perceptually grounded everyday concepts."}
